            "doi": null,
            "metadata": {
                "abstract": "\u00a9 The Author 2015. Published by Oxford University Press. Motivation: In the Wright-Fisher diffusion, the transition density function describes the time evolution of the population-wide frequency of an allele. This function has several practical applications in population genetics and computing it for biologically realistic scenarios with selection and demography is an important problem. Results: We develop an efficient method for finding a spectral representation of the transition density function for a general model where the effective population size, selection coefficients and mutation parameters vary over time in a piecewise constant manner.",
